Incorporation of these nanoparticles with CMC gives a significant improvement in tensile strength and also antibacterial activity to materials [26,27]. It is worth noting that due to the nanoparticle's large surface-to-ration property, these nanoparticles have the tendencies to agglomerate when applied individually. Hence, to overcome this matter, CMC has been used to be a stabilizer and minimize the agglomeration of these nanoparticles. This allows the boost of the nanoparticle capability to improve material properties not limited to antibacterial properties [7,28]. The mixture of CMC and these nanoparticles results in the formation of a colloidal solution with strong interfacial interaction with the CMC matrix, that can be used in material coating to help improve coated material's mechanical and antibacterial properties [27,29]. The flow phenomena of single phase flow or the solution flow consisting of suspended nanoparticles [30] in CMC colloidal solutions is worth studying as it elucidates the relation of CMC colloidal solution rheological properties with other properties in biomaterial characterisations. The relations between shear stress and shear rates of colloidal solution can be explained through Power Law or also known as Ostwald's Law equation (τ = K(γ)
                        n
                     ). τ indicates the shear stress, while K is the consistency factor, γ shear rate, and n represents the flow behaviour index. The flow behaviour index indicates whether the solution exhibits shear thickening (where n > 1) or shear thinning (where n < 1) which is further used to determine Newtonian or non-Newtonian fluids behaviour [31].
